<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10891&amp;p=124007#p124007</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10891&amp;p=124007#p124007"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Running Famicom carts in a NES]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10891&amp;p=124007#p124007"><![CDATA[
I don't recommand the Gyromite adapter AT ALL.<br /><br />I had to import a Gyromite cart all the way from USA just to get the adapter, and now it's eating dust in a drawer half destroyed somewhere. Because it's really impractical, ideally you'd have to place the PCB in the NES cart, and close it again and use it as a normal NES cart, but this only works for NROM-like Famicom PCBs, not very useful. Otherwise you'll have to deal with a bare PCB and trying to insert it into your NES, which is a terribly hard and annoying thing to do for both the front loader (you don't see what you're doing) and toploader (the connector is protected by a &quot;clapet&quot; (I have no idea how this word translate in english), and is hard to access )<br /><br />So if you want to be &quot;confortable&quot; get a real adapter and forget about Gyromite. The Gyromite game is absolutely terrible by the way, so at least you don't feel bad to destroy it ^^<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38">Bregalad</a> — Thu Jan 16, 2014 3:09 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
