<author><name><![CDATA[tokumaru]]></name></author>
<updated>2014-01-13T21:44:21-07:00</updated>
<published>2014-01-13T21:44:21-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10891&amp;p=123798#p123798</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10891&amp;p=123798#p123798"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Running Famicom carts in a NES]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10891&amp;p=123798#p123798"><![CDATA[
Many Gyromite carts with 5 screws have adapters inside. In addition to the 5 screws, the cart connector is also important for identifying adapters, as illustrated in <a href="http://www.racketboy.com/retro/hacks/gyromite-nes-import-adapter-guide" class="postlink">this page</a>.  I had to go through a few Gyromite carts before I found 2 that had adapters in them, and those were the 2 that had both characteristics: 5 screws and little lines extending from the side of the connector pins.<br /><br />Unfortunately there are very few Gyromite carts available on MercadoLivre right now, and the connectors are not visible in any of the pictures (plus, the carts are expensive as shit!).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Mon Jan 13, 2014 9:44 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
